<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So from first principles, if you want to be a =
climate investor, should you invest in coal companies? The intuitive answer=
 is no:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Burning coal is bad for the climate a=
nd you want less of it.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Presumably=
 your investment choices matter: You invest in things you want more of, so =
that there can be more of those things.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so there is a lot of green investing that =
takes the form =E2=80=9Cdo not finance fossil-fuel companies,=E2=80=9D or d=
o less of it or whatever. And that is a reasonable experiment to run. But t=
here are complications. For one thing, it=E2=80=99s not like=C2=A0<em>every=
=C2=A0</em>investor will be climate-focused. Coal companies will still have=
 investors, and if all the climate-focused investors dump the coal companie=
s, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.258409=
