<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Convertible bonds</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I used to be, among other things, a convertibl=
e bonds investment banker. This meant that I traveled around the country pi=
tching companies on issuing convertible bonds. The basic pitch is that a co=
nvertible bond lets you sell debt with a lower interest rate, by throwing i=
n an equity option. Instead of selling a bond that pays 7% interest, you se=
ll a bond that pays 2% interest, and if your stock goes up by 30%=C2=A0the =
bond converts into stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are various add-ons to this pitch =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0I should have worn a button saying =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21i=
ZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMTYvanBtb3JnYW4tZmlnaHRzLXRlc2x=
hLW92ZXItd2FycmFudHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDEwMzI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbW=
FpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMTAzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb=
25leXN0dWZmI2Zvb3Rlci1yZWYtZm9vdG5vdGUtMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB41607035=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">Ask Me About Tax Structuring!</a>=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but tha=
t=E2=80=99s the basic pitch. Intuitively, there is a sort of interest-rates=
 sweet spot for that pitch:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CInstead of selling a bond th=
at pays 1.5% interest, you sell a bond that pays 0% interest and can conver=
t into stock=E2=80=9D: Bad pitch. When straight debt is super-cheap, there=
=E2=80=99s no reason for good companies to mess around with converts.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CInstead of selling a bond tha=
t pays 7% interest, you sell a bond that pays 2% interest and can convert i=
nto stock=E2=80=9D: Good pitch. You save a lot of money!</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=E2=80=9CInstead of selling a bond that pays 17% i=
nterest, you sell a bond that pays 11% interest and can convert into stock=
=E2=80=9D: Bad pitch. When the convertible interest is super-high anyway, i=
t=E2=80=99s not that attractive.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I was a convertibles banker during a decent in=
terest-rate environment=C2=A0for convertibles. I remember it being cool whe=
n we could show a company a convertible with a 0% interest rate. Zero was a=
n excitingly low number, certainly=C2=A0much lower than whatever the compan=
y could get in the regular bond market.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CZero percent interest=
,=E2=80=9D we=E2=80=99d say. =E2=80=9CYou can=E2=80=99t afford not to!=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0 But that was a long time ago.=C2=A0A few years ago Apple Inc. =
issued a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.=
258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzMyMDE5My8wMDAx=
MTkzMTI1MTkyODg0MTIvZDgwNDIyNmQ0MjRiMi5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB21ed61=
82" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">six-year straight=C2=A0bond</a> that paid 0.00% interest. Conv=
ertibles can=E2=80=99t compete with that.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Probably 90% of everything in financial and bu=
siness news over the last decade could be described as a low-interest-rates=
 phenomenon, but convertible bonds are very much a medium-interest-rates ph=
enomenon, and now that medium interest rates are back so are convertibles. =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.258409/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvMjZmNDZlZTMtMWM3OC00NDM1LWEzMTUtNDcwMDI2N=
DNhMzll/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf9216244" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">The Financial Times repo=
rts</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US companies have been piling into the market =
for convertible bonds as they search for ways to keep their interest costs =
down, in a rare flurry of activity in otherwise subdued corporate fundraisi=
ng markets.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Issuance of convertible debt climbed by 77 per=
 cent last year to $48bn, according to data from LSEG, making it one of the=
 only areas of capital markets to return to pre-pandemic averages after 202=
2=E2=80=99s market downturn.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Experts say the boom in convertibles, a type o=
f bond that can be swapped for shares if a company=E2=80=99s stock price hi=
ts a pre-agreed level, is likely to continue this year as companies refinan=
ce a wave of maturing debt.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The debt has traditionally been popular with y=
ounger technology and biotech groups that struggle to access mainstream bon=
d markets. But more established companies have also dived in as the Federal=
 Reserve=E2=80=99s interest rate hikes have driven up borrowing costs even =
for investment-grade companies.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I confess that I am always=C2=A0rooting for th=
e convertibles market, both out of nostalgia and also because it seems vagu=
ely like some sort of career security for the skills of converts bankers to=
 be in demand.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Insider trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US insider trading law is weird. Most people h=
ave some rough=C2=A0intuition like =E2=80=9Cif you know about a merger that=
 hasn=E2=80=99t been announced yet, it is illegal to trade the stock of the=
 target,=E2=80=9D and in many countries that is roughly the law. (Not legal=
 advice, in any countries.) In the US, though, the law does not match close=
ly with that intuition. In the US, if you know about a merger that hasn=E2=
=80=99t been announced yet, it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>probably=C2=A0</em>illega=
l to trade on the stock of the target, but there needs to be some extra fac=
tor: You have to have gotten the information from an insider in exchange fo=
r a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.25840=
9/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDgtMjQvb=
WFydG9tYS1ydWxpbmctc2hvd3MtdGhhdC1ldmVyeXRoaW5nLWlzLWluc2lkZXItdHJhZGluZy1h=
Z2Fpbj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTAzMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3V=
yY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/60=
7f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB987dfcc7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsc=
ope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impo=
rtant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-botto=
m-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  personal benefit</a>, or you nee=
d to have violated some <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/=
click/33879916.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzL=
zIwMTQtMDgtMTgvb25lLWdvbGYtY291cnNlLXRoYXQtcy1ncmVhdC1mb3Itc3RvY2stdGlwcz9j=
bXBpZD1CQkQwMTAzMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV=
3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAxMDMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB930734af" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  duty of confidentiality</a> to the perso=
n you got the information from, or the merger needs to be a <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS92aWV3L2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTgtMDEtMDMvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4tcy1hbGxl=
cmdhbi1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRpbmctZGlzcHV0ZS1kb2Vzbi10LWxvb2stYmFkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA=
xMDMyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJn=
V0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDEwMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a2=
3cBff2d57f1" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blan=
k" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom=
-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;"> tender offer</a>. (Not legal advice, anywhere.)=C2=A0=
There is not just a rule that says =E2=80=9Cif you know about a merger that=
 hasn=E2=80=99t been announced yet, it is illegal to trade the stock of the=
 target.=E2=80=9D Instead there is=C2=A0a hodgepodge of other rules that al=
most, but not quite, add up to that general rule.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think this is broadly good =E2=80=94 a rule =
saying =E2=80=9Cyou can never trade on any information that isn=E2=80=99t p=
ublic=E2=80=9D would discourage analysts from finding out new facts =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but that=E2=80=99s not the point. The point is that US insider tra=
ding law is complicated, a collection of specific rules rather than a gener=
al prohibition, and it=C2=A0changes over time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In particular, for a long time, it was=C2=A0<e=
m>roughly</em><em>=C2=A0</em>true that:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you worked for the <em>target</em> =
of a merger, and you knew about the merger in advance, you couldn=E2=80=99t=
 trade your company=E2=80=99s stock: You were an insider, and that would be=
 insider trading.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgr=
ound-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> As an insider of the company, you had a fiduciary duty to the sharehol=
ders not to take advantage of them by trading on inside information.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If you worked at the=C2=A0<em>acquirer=
</em>, and you knew about the merger in advance, you=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</=
em>trade the target=E2=80=99s stock.=C2=A0You weren=E2=80=99t an insider of=
 the=C2=A0<em>target</em>, just of the acquirer; you had no fiduciary duty =
to the target=E2=80=99s shareholders so you could go ahead and trade.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not legal advice, in the past, or now. But at =
least some courts took this view. And then in 1997, the=C2=A0US Supreme Cou=
rt <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.258409=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdXByZW1lLmp1c3RpYS5jb20vY2FzZXMvZmVkZXJhbC91cy81MjEvNjQyLw/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB285639a3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">expanded the law</a>=C2=A0in a case=
 called <em>US v. O=E2=80=99Hagan</em>,=C2=A0endorsing=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Cmisa=
ppropriation=E2=80=9D theory that made it illegal for anyone to trade on no=
npublic information that they misappropriated from anyone, including acquir=
er insiders trading target stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Intuitively you might think something like: =
=E2=80=9CWell, before 1997, it was basically legal in the US for people who=
 knew about a merger in advance =E2=80=94=C2=A0not all of them, but at leas=
t the acquirer=E2=80=99s employees and bankers and lawyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
o trade in the target=E2=80=99s stock, so there must have been a ton of ins=
ider trading in advance of merger news. And then after 1997, it was basical=
ly illegal for most of those people to do that, so all that insider trading=
 must have stopped.=E2=80=9D There are of course flaws in that logic:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Before 1997 it was at best ambiguously=
 legal to do this. (O=E2=80=99Hagan himself =E2=80=94=C2=A0who worked at an=
 acquirer=E2=80=99s law firm=C2=A0and bought call options on the target =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0was arrested and convicted of insider trading, though an appeal=
s court threw out his conviction, before the Supreme Court reinstated it.)<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">After 1997 the legality is still s=
omewhat complex, and there is not a clear blanket ban on trading on inside =
knowledge of a merger.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Not everyon=
e who might do insider trading follows the nuances of Supreme Court insider=
 trading jurisprudence, so they might not update their behavior immediately=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some people wouldn=E2=80=99t hav=
e done this even when it was legal, because it seemed shady, and other peop=
le will do it even when it=E2=80=99s illegal, because it=E2=80=99s lucrativ=
e and they don=E2=80=99t expect to get caught.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still you could imagine that 1997 would be a s=
tep change in the amount of insider trading on mergers. And I suppose it wa=
s. Here are a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3387=
9916.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly9wYXBlcnMuc3Nybi5jb20vc29sMy9wYXBlcnMuY2ZtP2Fic3RyYWN=
0X2lkPTQ2MjczMjc/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCae8cd3f4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> fun paper</a> =
and <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.25840=
9/aHR0cHM6Ly9jbHNibHVlc2t5Lmxhdy5jb2x1bWJpYS5lZHUvMjAyNC8wMS8wMy9ob3ctdGhlL=
W1pc2FwcHJvcHJpYXRpb24tdGhlb3J5LWFmZmVjdHMtdGhlLWFtb3VudC1vZi1pbnNpZGVyLXRy=
YWRpbmcv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd7cabf90" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscop=
e=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration:=
 none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; b=
order-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> related blog post</a> =
by Fernan Restrepo about =E2=80=9CHow the Misappropriation Theory Affects t=
he Amount of Insider Trading=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My paper tests this hypothesis by examining th=
e impact of <em>O=E2=80=99Hagan</em> on a common proxy for insider trading:=
 target run-ups in mergers and acquisitions (=E2=80=9CM&amp;A=E2=80=9D) =E2=
=80=93 that is, the cumulative abnormal returns for the shares of the targe=
t company before the transaction is publicly announced. The intuition behin=
d this proxy is that individuals who hold non-public information about merg=
ers and acquisitions can make significant profits if they buy shares in the=
 target company before the transaction is announced (since mergers typicall=
y involve the payment of a large premium over market prices); as a result, =
a significant increase in the target=E2=80=99s pre-merger price is likely i=
ndicative of a high incidence of trading on confidential information about =
the transaction. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The results show that the run-ups in fact decr=
eased significantly in relation to the announcement returns after <em>O=E2=
=80=99Hagan</em>. Before <em>O=E2=80=99Hagan</em>, the average relative run=
-up was 7 percentage points lower than the announcement returns; after the =
decision, the difference became 9 percentage points. In this sense, after O=
=E2=80=99Hagan, there was less anticipatory trading explaining the overall =
valuation effect of M&amp;A bids, which is consistent with the notion of le=
ss insider trading.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose a thought experiment would be: If th=
e US got rid of its current rules and replaced them with a simpler, =E2=80=
=9Cif you know about a merger that hasn=E2=80=99t been announced yet, it is=
 illegal to trade the stock of the target=E2=80=9D-style rule, would that c=
hange the average run-up? My guess is no: My guess is that the current hodg=
epodge of rules covers basically every practical situation, so expanding th=
em wouldn=E2=80=99t have much effect.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#f=
ootnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: non=
e !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-blo=
ck;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But I=E2=80=99m not sure.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
