order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote yesterday</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Basically if you watch a football =
game on television, you see what happens shortly after the sportsbook does,=
 and they can update their odds of something happening before you see it ha=
ppen. The sportsbook has a direct feed from the NFL, whereas you rely on th=
e consolidated tape of watching the game on TV. If you are at the game in p=
erson can you front-run the sportsbook on your phone? A little bit? I am go=
ing to get 200 emails about this. At least one of my readers has surely fro=
nt-run a sportsbook.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Not literally 200, but, yes, I heard from a lo=
t of readers about front-running=C2=A0sportsbooks.<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> It is classically called =E2=80=9Ccourtsiding,=E2=80=9D because the wa=
y to get data faster than the sportsbooks=E2=80=99 direct feeds is by sitti=
ng courtside. One reader even pointed me to a book about it; from <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/33879916.258409/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9HYW1lLVNldC1DYXNoLUludGVybmF0aW9uYWwtVHJhZGluZy9kcC8x=
ODYzOTU2NTlY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB15485909" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the Amazon summary=
</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Brad Hutchins has been living a yo=
ung bloke's dream: getting paid to travel the world and watch sport. Sittin=
g court-side on the pro tennis circuit, he uses his phone to transmit resul=
ts to a gambling syndicate, taking advantage of the time delay in TV broadc=
asts to beat other online punters to the big pay-offs. His stories from lif=
e on the road capture the adventures and mishaps that come with following t=
he world's best tennis players and partying in a new country every week. Bu=
t like card counters in casinos, court-siders are despised by the tennis es=
tablishment. The more time Brad spends at tournaments, the harder it become=
s for him to evade the security guards who are hell-bent on ejecting him fr=
om matches. The resulting cat-and-mouse chases will appeal to anyone who lo=
ves the roguish spirit of The Wolf of Wall Street or Catch Me If You Can.</=
p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or <em>Flash Boys </em>I guess. Another reader=
 pointed me to <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/338=
79916.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmFpbGlpLm9yZy9ldy9jYXNlcy9FV0NBL0Npdi8yMDIwLz=
EzMDAuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa3a9ac53" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a UK legal case</a=
> about it, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/338799=
16.258409/aHR0cHM6Ly9saXR0bGV0b25jaGFtYmVycy5jb20vYXJ0aWNsZXMtd2ViaW5hcnMvc=
mFjaW5nLXBhcnRuZXJzaGlwcy1sdGQtdi1zcG9ydHMtaW5mb3JtYXRpb24tc2VydmljZXMtbHRk=
LWNvdXJ0LW9mLWFwcGVhbC1zaGVkcy1saWdodC1vbi1lY29ub21pYy10b3J0cy1vZi1icmVhY2g=
tb2YtY29uZmlkZW5jZS1hbmQtdW5sYXdmdWwtbWVhbnMtY29uc3BpcmFjeS8/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBc420b822" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> which</a> =E2=80=9Carose out of an agreement=
 for the provision of live betting and horseracing data from certain raceco=
urses=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lewison LJ (with whom Phillips LJ =
agreed) took what may be regarded as a less legalistic and more pragmatic a=
pproach towards the question of confidentiality. In his view, the fact that=
 a large amount of the information concerned would be broadcast live on tel=
evision, and thereby almost instantly available to the public at large, mad=
e it difficult to argue that the information =E2=80=93 at least individuall=
y =E2=80=93 was confidential. His Lordship cited Lord Walker=E2=80=99s mino=
rity opinion in=C2=A0<em>Douglas v. Hello!</em>=C2=A0suggesting that commer=
cial value alone is not enough, and that=C2=A0<em>=E2=80=9Cthe confidential=
ity of any information must depend on its nature, not its market value=E2=
=80=9D</em>. Lord Walker stated that the law of confidentiality should not=
=C2=A0<em>=E2=80=9Cafford the protection of exclusivity in a [public] spect=
acle=E2=80=9D</em>.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that was the minority view. Another reader=
 pointed out that the <em>reason</em>=C2=A0venues eject courtsiders is the =
economic value of their live feeds: Venues make money by selling live feeds=
 to sportsbooks, but courtsiders reduce the value of those feeds to the spo=
rtsbooks and, thus, the venue.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yet another reader sent me this 2021 Wired sto=
ry with the impeccable title =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
